05392nam a22007935i 9780812203943DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013957182  a(OCoLC)979904791  a97808122039437 a10.9783/97808122039432doi  a(DE-B1597)449318  a(OCoLC)802047770  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a381.082/09731 aHartigan-O'Connor, Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ties That Buy :bWomen and Commerce in Revolutionary America /cEllen Hartigan-O'Connor. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b18 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Urban Housefuls -- tChapter 2. Work in the Atlantic Service Economy -- tChapter 3. Family Credit and Shared Debts -- tChapter 4. Translating Money -- tChapter 5. Shopping Networks and Consumption as Collaboration -- tChapter 6 The Republic of Goods -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1770, tavernkeeper Abigail Stoneman called in her debts by flourishing a handful of playing cards before the Rhode Island Court of Common Pleas. Scrawled on the cards were the IOUs of drinkers whose links to Stoneman testified to women's paradoxical place in the urban economy of the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Stoneman did traditional women's work—boarding, feeding, cleaning, and selling alcohol—but her customers, like her creditors, underscore her connections to an expansive commercial society. These connections are central to The Ties That Buy.Historian Ellen Hartigan-O'Connor traces the lives of urban women in early America to reveal how they used the ties of residence, work, credit, and money to shape consumer culture at a time when the politics of the marketplace was gaining national significance. Covering the period 1750-1820, the book analyzes how women such as Stoneman used and were used by shifting forms of credit and cash in an economy transitioning between neighborly exchanges and investment-oriented transactions. In this world, commerce reached into every part of life. At the hearths of multifamily homes, renters, lodgers, and recent acquaintances lived together and struck financial deals for survival. Landladies, enslaved washerwomen, shopkeepers, and hucksters sustained themselves by serving the mobile population. A new economic practice in America—shopping—mobilized hierarchical and friendly relationships into wide-ranging consumer networks that depended on these same market connections.Rhetoric emerging after the Revolution downplayed the significance of expanding female economic life in the interest of stabilizing the political order. But women were quintessential market participants, with fluid occupational identities, cross-class social and economic connections, and a firm investment in cash and commercial goods for power and meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHouseholdsxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenxEconomic conditions. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954